'''''QI''''', standing for ''Quite Interesting'' (and a play on "[[Intelligence quotient|IQ]]"), is a comedy [[panel game]] television show hosted by [[Stephen Fry]], and featuring regular panellist [[Alan Davies]]. It is broadcast on [[BBC Two]] and [[BBC Four]], while older, syndicated episodes are shown on [[UKTV G2]]. ''QI'' is one of the most successful shows shown on its channel, having the highest ratings of any show on BBC Four.<ref>[http://www.qi.com/tv/audience.php QI.com] Audience figures. Accessed [[21 June]], [[2007]].</ref>

It is distinguished by the awarding of points not necessarily for the ''correct'' answer, but rather, for an ''interesting'' one. Many of the questions and answers are extremely obscure. Points are deducted from a panellist who gives an ''obvious but wrong'' (that is to say, boring or conventional) answer, typically one that is generally accepted as true but is, in fact, false. It is therefore possible (and quite likely) that a panellist will have a negative point score at the end of the game.

== Format and Conception ==
[[Image:QI Logo.png|thumb|right|The QI Logo.]]
The panel consists of four panellists: three rotating and one regular, Alan Davies, who has the seat to Stephen Fry's right. Davies is the frequent target of jokes — mainly initiated by Stephen Fry — and because, generally, he offers up most of the "obvious but wrong" answers, he usually finishes last, having only won three times.

Most of the show's panellists come from a [[stand-up comedy]] background, although there have also been other famous entertainment personalities including [[Richard E. Grant]], [[Jeremy Clarkson]], [[Graeme Garden]], [[Gyles Brandreth]], [[Anneka Rice]] and [[Roger McGough]].

Questions are sometimes misleading or fiendishly difficult. Providing an "obvious but wrong" answer results in a sequence of [[klaxon]]s. In the first and second series, Stephen Fry produced the answer on a card to show the panellists, while it also flashed on the large screens behind them (excepting the very first episode, when only the cards were used).<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series A, Episode 1 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (A series) | airdate = 2003-09-11 | season = A | number = 1 }}</ref> In the third series and onward, Fry's answer cards were dispensed with altogether, leaving only the screens as proof that the answers given had been predicted. Because of the show's expectation that hardly anyone would be able to give a correct answer without significant prompting, it instead encourages sheer interestingness. As such, tangential discussions and even complete non-sequiturs abound on the show, for panellists are apt to branch off into frivolous conversations, give voice to train of thought, and share humorous anecdotes from their own lives.

=== Buzzers ===
Each of the panel has a [[buzzer]], the sound of which is often based along some sort of theme. The sounds are demonstrated at the beginning of the programme, but are sometimes changed in some way the very next time they are used. Davies's buzzer usually contradicts the others' in some amusing way.  Davies's buzzer has been the last to be demonstrated in every episode except for the unbroadcast pilot, in which he went first and Eddie Izzard, with a sillier buzzer, went last.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Pilot | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (A series)}}</ref>

=== General Ignorance ===
{{main|General Ignorance}}
[[Image:QIfront.JPG|thumb|225px|right|Stephen Fry presenting an episode of ''QI''.]]
In a parody of ubiquitous [[general knowledge]] quizzes, the final round is off-topic and called "General Ignorance", focusing upon seemingly-easy questions which have "obvious but wrong" answers. Whereas in the main rounds of the show, the panellists' use of buzzers is not usually enforced, the "General Ignorance" questions are introduced by Fry's reminder to keep "fingers on buzzers".

One Christmas episode saw Davies making a stand and announcing that he didn't want to do General Ignorance because he always got the questions wrong, saying that he "will not ''be'' humiliated at Christmas". In turn, Fry offered to switch places with him, to the delight of the audience. Despite the seeming spontaneity of the swap, it was undoubtedly pre-planned (at least on the part of Davies and the producers), as evidenced by the fact that Davies, in turn, produced his own set of questions on loose-leaf paper, most of which he directed at Fry. At the end of the show, Fry announced that the game's loser was, in fact, he himself, as a result of his conceding to many of Davies' traps.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Christmas Special | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (B series) | airdate = 2004-12-26 | season = B | number = 12 }}</ref>

=== Extra tasks ===
In some episodes, panellists are given an extra task to complete during the course of the game. Those who do the best are often awarded extra points. Sometimes the task is as simple as competing in a drawing contest; other times, the panel are told to look for a specific hidden thing over the course of the show, such as a [[squirrel]]<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series C, Episode11 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (C series) | airdate = 2005-12-09 | season = C | number = 11 }}</ref> or [[cuttlefish]].<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series C, Episode 9 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (C series) | airdate = 2005-11-25 | season = C | number = 9 }}</ref>  One of the most famous tasks was set in series 2, when each member of the panel were given a magnetic letterboard with which they were to spell out words throughout the show. Although most of the panel were content with demonstrating short and amusing phrases, Jimmy Carr astounded team and audience alike by using all of his letters to say, "Put Smarties tubes on cats legs/make them walk like a robot".<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series B, Episode 5 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (B series) | airdate = 2004-11-05 | season = 2 | episode = 5 }}</ref>

==Production==
[[Image:QI Davies.jpg|thumb|225px|right|Alan Davies on ''QI''.]]
Writer and former [[BBC]] producer [[John Lloyd (writer)|John Lloyd]] devised the format of the show, and it is produced by Quite Interesting Ltd., an organisation set up by Lloyd. ''QI'' was originally conceived as a radio show, with Lloyd as chairman. When it was decided that the show would air on television, [[Michael Palin]] was offered the job of chairman with Fry and Davies as captains of "clever" and "stupid" teams, respectively.<ref>[http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2006/12/21/4850/last_among_eqials Chortle.co.uk "Last among eQIals"] Written [[21 December]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[21 June]], [[2007]].</ref>

The research for the show is mostly carried out by the [[Cultural impact of QI#The QI Elves|QI Elves]]. The elves also devise the questions, and are sometimes even contact the show part way through to provide and even correct information given by the contestants.<ref name="Elves">[http://www.qi.com/about/people.php#elves www.qi.com] The QI Elves, accessed [[17 January]] [[2007]]</ref> Other people involved in researching questions are John Mitchinson and Piers Fletcher, known as the ''Question Wranglers''.<ref name="Elves"/>

The theme tune was composed by [[Howard Goodall]], who has twice appeared as a panellist on the show. However, originally the theme music was going to be the song [[Wonderful World (song)|Wonderful World]], sung by [[Herman's Hermits]], which was used in the unbroadcast pilot. However, they were forbidden the use of the song, and the DVD recording of the pilot now uses the theme music composed by Goodall.<ref name="Factoid">''QI Series 1 DVD'' Factoids</ref>

Some people have suggested that answers to questions are rehearsed in advance, in order to provide a more entertaining programme, an accusation also headed towards shows such as ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''. On the official website, the makers of the show insist that this is not the case. The panel are given a list of questions set to be asked just about an hour before the show, and before recording starts, they run through a series of "warm up" questions; this is the only assistance the panellists receive. They are forbidden to ask for preparatory materials or other help.<ref name="Factoid"/> It is known that Alan never does any preparation at all.<ref name="Factoid"/>

The show also uses a warm-up comedian before recording begins. In the forthcoming series, the warm-up was [[Stephen Grant]].<ref>[http://www.stephengrant.com/sg_television.htm#warmup Stephen Grant.com, Warm Up] Accessed [[23 June]], [[2007]].</ref>

==Episodes==
[[Image:QI-Series 1.jpg|thumb|right|''QI Series 1'' DVD cover, with Alan Davies on the left and Stephen Fry on the right.]]
{{seealso|List of QI episodes}}

In ''QI'', every series is themed around a different letter of the alphabet, starting with the letter "A". Series are therefore referred to by letter rather than number. 

In Series A, which started on [[11 September]] [[2003]], all of the questions (with the exception of the final "General Ignorance" round) were on subjects beginning with "a" except in the Christmas Special (e.g., "[[arthropods]]", "[[Alan (name)|Alan]]s", "[[astronomy]]", etc.)

Series B started on [[8 October]] [[2004]], with most of episodes having "B" themes (e.g., "[[Bird|Birds]]", "[[Berry|berries]]"), except in two episodes, one about [[music]] and one about [[colour]].

Series C started on [[30 September]] [[2005]], and all subjects began with the letter "C" (e.g. "[[custard]], [[cheating]]").

Series D, started on [[29 September]] [[2006]]. This series differed from the previous three as all episodes focused upon a single "D" topic (with subsidiary lines of inquiry), examples of which are [[Danger]], [[Death]], [[Domestic]](as in cleaning) and [[Dog]]s.

The fifth series, Series E, has been recorded. For more information on the forthcoming series, see [[List of QI episodes (E series)|Series E article]].

It has also been announced that ''QI'' is to create a [[Video podcast|vodcast]] for Series E.<ref>[http://qitalk.blogspot.com/2007/05/qi-e05-recording-review.html QI E05 Recording Review] QI Talk on blogspot. Created [[25 May]] [[2007]]. Accessed [[27 May]] [[2007]].</ref>

