Many of the frequent participants are managed by the ''Off the Kerb Productions'' comedy group.

==Highlights==

===Pluto and Cruithne===
The questions are, as in many comedy panel games, mainly created to set up jokes or discussions, rather than for any serious competition. Certain questions are purposely contradictory to established doctrine for the sake of entertainment. For example, to the question "How many planets are there in the solar system?", Alan Davies gave the answer "Nine" and lost points for an "obvious but wrong" answer, the explanation being that at the time a debate was occurring over whether [[Pluto (planet)|Pluto]] was indeed a planet (see ''[[2006 definition of planet]]''). However, as the [[International Astronomical Union]] still defined Pluto as a planet at the time of questioning, the answer "nine" ''would'' have been a "correct" answer, if one accepted the contemporaneous IAU definition.<ref name="SAE2">{{cite episode | title = Series A, Episode 2 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (A series) | airdate = 2003-09-18 | season = A | number = 2 }}</ref>

A further example of this purposeful contradiction occurred during the second series, when the question "How many moons does the Earth have?" was asked. Alan Davies had, in the previous series, been given a penalty for answering "One" to the same question, due to the presence of the [[asteroid]] [[3753 Cruithne|Cruithne]] which has an [[orbital resonance]] with Earth (although it is not normally defined as a [[natural satellite]]).<ref name="SAE2"/> This time, he was again given negative points for answering with "two", which was counted as correct during the first series. The change in answer was attributed to the recent discovery of new satellites ([[(54509) 2000 PH5|(54509) 2000 PH<sub>5</sub>]], [[(85770) 1998 UP1|(85770) 1998 UP<sub>1</sub>]] and [[2002 AA29|2002 AA<sub>29</sub>]]) that share a similar resonance to Cruithne with respect to the Earth.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series B, Episode 6 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (B series) | airdate = 2004-11-12 | season = B | number = 6 }}</ref>

===Luvvie Alarm===
A "Luvvie Alarm" has on occasion sounded when a guest blatantly [[name-dropping|name-drops]]. It was originally used on [[John Sessions]] when he name dropped [[Robert Redford]] in series 2.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series B, Episode 10 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (B series) | airdate = 2005-12-10 | season = B | number = 10 }}</ref> It was later used on Fry when he mentioned a party he had attended hosted by the [[Gerald Grosvenor, 6th Duke of Westminster|Duke and Duchess of Westminster]] (as pointed out by guest [[Clive Anderson]], the Duke was (at the time of recording) the second richest man in the UK after [[Roman Abramovich]]; [[as of 2006]], he is currently third-richest after Abramovich and [[Lakshmi Mittal]]).<ref name="SCE10">{{cite episode | title = Series C, Episode 10 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (C series) | airdate = 2005-12-02 | season = C | number = 10 }}</ref>

===Corrections and Mistakes===
At the end of the third series, [[Dara Ó Briain]] was deducted points for having stated, in the series before, that the [[triple point]] of [[water]] is zero degrees [[Celsius]], an answer which earned him points at the time.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series B, Episode 7 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (B series) | airdate = 2005-11-19 | season = B | number = 7 }}</ref> Some viewers, however, wrote in to say that the triple point of water is in fact ''0.01'' degrees, and so the points awarded Dara in the previous series were revoked. Dara humorously retorted with, "How many people sat at home watching that and said, 'It's just a comedy show, but I'm not letting that [[feck]]er get away with that!'?"<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series C, Episode 12 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (C series) | airdate = 2005-12-16 | season = C | number = 12 }}</ref>

Although most of the facts presented on the show are correct, there has been the occasional slip-up. Several facts given are often updated and corrected in later series. For example, in Series A, the show claimed that the longest animal in the world was the [[lion's mane jellyfish]],<ref>{{cite episode | title = Series A, Episode 3 | series = QI | serieslink = List of QI episodes (A series) | airdate = 2003-09-25 | season = A | number = 3 }}</ref> but this was later corrected in Series C, saying that the longest animal on the world is the [[Lineus longissimus|bootlace worm]].<ref name="SCE10"/>

==''QI'' culture==
{{main|Cultural impact of QI}}

''QI'' has had an impact on British culture. There have been several DVDs and books, most notable ''The Book of General Ignorance'', which was a best seller on [[amazon.co.uk]].<ref>{{cite web | title = QI Talk Forum, The Forum of General Ignorance, "Book of General Ignorance Hits Top 25 on Amazon!" | date = 2006-12-08 | url = http://www.qi.com/talk/viewtopic.php?t=4514&postdays=0&postorder=asc&highlight=selling+general+ignorance&start=135 | accessdate = 2007-06-22 }}</ref> ''QI'' also has a club in [[Oxford]], a large website, a section in ''[[The Telegraph]]''.

''QI'' has its own [[philosophy]]. It states that everything in the world, even what appear to be the most boring things, are quite interesting, if looked at in the right way. The website states that:

<blockquote>
"We live, they say, in The Information Age, yet almost none of the information we think we possess is true. [[Eskimo|Eskimos]] do not rub noses. The [[rickshaw]] was invented by an American. [[Joan of Arc]] was not French. [[Lenin]] was not Russian. The world is not solid, it is made of empty space and energy, and neither [[haggis]], [[whisky]], [[porridge]], [[clan tartans]] nor [[kilt|kilts]] are [[Scotland|Scottish]]. So we stand, silent, on a peak in Darien: a vast, rolling, teeming, untrodden territory before us. QI country. Whatever is interesting we are interested in. Whatever is not interesting, we are even more interested in. Everything is interesting if looked at ''in the right way''. At one extreme, QI is serious, intensely scientific, deeply mystical; at the other it is hilarious, silly and frothy enough to please the most indolent couch-potato."<ref>[http://www.qi.com/about/philosophy.php QI.com, Philosophy.] Accessed [[15 June]] [[2007]].</ref>
</blockquote>

==Awards==
Currently, ''QI'' has won only one award. In [[2006]], Fry won the [[Rose d'Or]] for "Best Game Show Host".<ref name="Awards">[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0380136/awards Internet Movie Database, QI, Awards] Accessed [[23 June]], [[2007]].</ref>

''QI'' has been nominated for four [[BAFTA|BAFTAs]]. Fry has been nominated for "Best Entertainment Performance" three times, in [[2004]], [[2005]] and [[2007]]. John Lloyd and ''QI's'' director [[Ian Lorimer]] were nominated for the Lew Grade Award in 2005.<ref name="Awards"/>

